<p>A <b>Shepard tone</b>, named after <a href="/wiki/Roger_Shepard" title="Roger Shepard">Roger Shepard</a>, is a <a href="/wiki/Sound" title="Sound">sound</a> consisting of a superposition of sine waves separated by <a href="/wiki/Octave" title="Octave">octaves</a>. When played with the base <a href="/wiki/Pitch_(music)" title="Pitch (music)">pitch</a> of the tone moving upwards or downwards, it is referred to as the <i>Shepard scale</i>. This creates the <a href="/wiki/Auditory_illusion" title="Auditory illusion">auditory illusion</a> of a tone that continually ascends or descends in pitch, yet which ultimately seems to get no higher or lower.<sup id="cite_ref-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-0" title=""><span>[</span>1<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
